        <div n="086-404P" type="poem"><head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-086-404P-headnote-1"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-086-404P-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-086-404P-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head><head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-086-404P-headnote-2"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-086-404P-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-086-404P-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head><head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-086-404P-headnote-3"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-086-404P-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-086-404P-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head>
      <lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-1"><hi rend="display-initial">W</hi>hen mother Clud had rose from play</l><l n="2" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-2"> And call'd to take the Cards away</l><l n="3" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-3"> Van saw but seem'd not to regard</l><l n="4" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-4"> How Miss pick't ev'ry painted Card</l><l n="5" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-5"> And busy both with hand, &amp; Eye</l><l n="6" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-6"> Soon rear'd a House two Story's high</l><l n="7" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-7"> Van's Genius (without thought or Lecture)</l><l n="8" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-8"> This highly turn'd to Architecture</l><l n="9" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-9"> He saw the Edifice and Smil'd</l><l n="10" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-10"> Vow'd it was pretty for a Child</l><l n="11" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-11"> It was so perfect in it's kind</l><l n="12" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-12"> He kept the Model in his mind</l><l n="13" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-13"> But when he found the Boys at play</l><l n="14" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-14"> And saw them dabbling in their Clay</l><l n="15" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-15"> He stood behind a Stall to lurk</l><l n="16" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-16"> And mark the progress of their Work</l><l n="17" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-17"> With true delight observ'd 'em all</l><l n="18" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-18"> Raking up Mudd to build a Wall</l><l n="19" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-19"> The plan he much admir'd &amp; took</l><l n="20" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-20"> The Model in his Table-book</l><l n="21" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-21"> Thought himself now exactly Skill'd</l><l n="22" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-22"> And so resolv'd a House to build</l><l n="23" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-23"> A real House w<hi rend="sup">thÌ£</hi> Rooms &amp; Stairs</l><l n="24" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-24"> Five times at least as big as theirs</l><l n="25" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-25"> Taller than Misses by Two yards</l><l n="26" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-26"> Not a sham thing of Clay, or Cards</l><l n="27" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-27"> And So he did for in a While</l><l n="28" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-28"> He built up Such a monstrous Pile</l><l n="29" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-29"> That no two Chairmen could be found</l><l n="30" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-30"> Able to lift it from the Ground</l><l n="31" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-31"> Still at Whitehall it stands in view</l><l n="32" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-32"> Just in the place where first it grew</l><l n="33" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-33"> There all the little Schoolboys run</l><l n="34" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-34"> Envying to see themselves outdone</l><l n="35" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-35"> From such deep rudiments as these</l><l n="36" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-36"> Van is become by due degrees</l><l n="37" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-37"> For building fam'd &amp; justly reckon'd</l><l n="38" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-38"> At Court Vitruvius the second</l><l n="39" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-39"> No Wonder! Since wise authors Show</l><l n="40" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-40"> That best foundations should be low</l><l n="41" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-41"> And now the Duke has wisely ta'ne him</l><l n="42" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-42"> To be his Architect at Blenheim</l><l n="43" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-43"> But raillery for once apart</l><l n="44" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-44"> If this rule holds in ev'ry Art</l><l n="45" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-45"> Or if his Grace were no more skill'd in</l><l n="46" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-46"> The Art of Batt'ring Walls than building</l><l n="47" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-47"> We might expect to find next year</l><l n="48" xml:id="spp-086-404P-line-48"> A Mouse-Trapman Chief Engineer.086-404P   </l></lg></div>
